T1  - Generalizability of Individual Difference Moderators of the Participation in Decision Making-Employee Response Relationship
AU  - White, J. Kenneth
Y1  - 1978/03/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255660
DO  - 10.5465/255660
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 36
EP  - 43
VL  - 21
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A considerable amount of research including numerous replications has indicated that individual difference moderators of the relationship between the job situation and employee responses do not generalize across research sites. Using data from 2,431 employees in 14 research sites, the present study hypothesized and found that such moderating effects are situation-specific. Not one of 73 potential moderator variables investigated consistently moderated the relationship between participation and job attitudes across all 14 research locations.
AB  - A considerable amount of research including numerous replications has indicated that individual difference moderators of the relationship between the job situation and employee responses do not generalize across research sites. Using data from 2,431 employees in 14 research sites, the present study hypothesized and found that such moderating effects are situation-specific. Not one of 73 potential moderator variables investigated consistently moderated the relationship between participation and job attitudes across all 14 research locations.
