T1  - The Effects of Sex, Marital Status, and Educational Background on Selection Decisions
AU  - Renwick, Patricia Ann
AU  - Tosi, Henry
Y1  - 1978/03/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255665
DO  - 10.5465/255665
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 93
EP  - 103
VL  - 21
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Graduate students in administration (n = 80) rated bogus resumes on applicant suitability for two managerial positions in a simulation of the conditions typically encountered by decision makers in selection situations. An analysis of variance indicated that both undergraduate major and graduate degree influenced ratings of suitability. Significant interactions were observed for job type and graduate degree and for job type and marital status. Finally, a significant interaction for sex, marital status, undergraduate major and graduate degree suggested that certain configurations of applicant characteristics were perceived as more suitable than others.
AB  - Graduate students in administration (n = 80) rated bogus resumes on applicant suitability for two managerial positions in a simulation of the conditions typically encountered by decision makers in selection situations. An analysis of variance indicated that both undergraduate major and graduate degree influenced ratings of suitability. Significant interactions were observed for job type and graduate degree and for job type and marital status. Finally, a significant interaction for sex, marital status, undergraduate major and graduate degree suggested that certain configurations of applicant characteristics were perceived as more suitable than others.
