JO  - AMJ
SP  - 104
EP  - 112
VL  - 21
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Subjects evaluated hypothetical male and female applicants for managerial positions. Half required supervision of predominately female subordinates; half the supervision of predominately male subordinates. Females expected higher performance than males. Males and females favored applicants whose sex matched the subordinates'. Thus, the sex-role context, not merely the applicant's sex, may induce selection discrimination.
AB  - Subjects evaluated hypothetical male and female applicants for managerial positions. Half required supervision of predominately female subordinates; half the supervision of predominately male subordinates. Females expected higher performance than males. Males and females favored applicants whose sex matched the subordinates'. Thus, the sex-role context, not merely the applicant's sex, may induce selection discrimination.
