T1  - Effects of Pay Disclosure on Satisfaction for Sales Managers: A Longitudinal Study
AU  - Futrell, Charles M.
Y1  - 1978/03/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255671
DO  - 10.5465/255671
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 140
EP  - 144
VL  - 21
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a study which examined the effects of pay disclosure on job satisfaction for sales managers. The author points out prior studies on the relationship between an open pay policy and various facets of job satisfaction. The impact of the implementation of an open pay policy on the pay and promotion satisfaction of managers was found to increase job satisfaction. A chart is presented that list the post-test minus pretest managers' satisfaction means by groups and sales regions. It was also found that the differences in satisfaction between the experimental and control groups varied considerably.
AB  - The article discusses a study which examined the effects of pay disclosure on job satisfaction for sales managers. The author points out prior studies on the relationship between an open pay policy and various facets of job satisfaction. The impact of the implementation of an open pay policy on the pay and promotion satisfaction of managers was found to increase job satisfaction. A chart is presented that list the post-test minus pretest managers' satisfaction means by groups and sales regions. It was also found that the differences in satisfaction between the experimental and control groups varied considerably.
